<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-808-718  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 808 718.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Sept 3 1990 v24 n36 p70(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Your next move may be on you: corporate cost controls are takingthe wind out of paid relocation benefits.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ruhl, Janet.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many technical recruiters are reporting that the number ofemployers willing to pay relocation costs for newly hiredemployees is down sharply over recent years.andP;  Observers say thatemployers in major urban areas where housing costs are high, andthe pool of available talent large, are the most reluctant to payfor relocating an employee.andP;  In comparison, employers in theSoutheast and Midwest, where housing costs are lower, and thenumber of qualified employees small, are more willing to paymoving expenses.andP;  In general, employees in the $20,000 to $40,000salary range, with hands-on technical experience, are the mostlikely to receive relocation money.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Employee BenefitsComputer industryEmployment OpportunityHiring.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>